<%=AppModTitleFont%>
To work better with a High D Leader…
<%=EndAppModTitleFont%>
<%=EndAppModParaFont%>

<%=AppModParaFont%>
&#149;	Get to the point. Don't provide too much detail.<br>
&#149;	Be assertive, but don't do all the talking.<br>
&#149;	Be more optimistic and enthusiastic than you usually are.<br>
&#149;	Hit the high points; concentrate on results and achieving goals.<br>
&#149;	Stress the what, not the why. Be solution-oriented.<br>
&#149;	Convey a sense of urgency. Respect the High D's use of time.<br>
&#149;	Provide risk assessments, and be prepared to take some risks.<br>
&#149;	Meet deadlines. Don't over-analyze or over-plan.<br>
&#149;	Prioritize; concentrate on what's really important.<br>
&#149;	Don't overwhelm the High D with written materials.<br>
&#149;	Be tolerant of criticism; you're likely to get plenty of it.<br>
&#149;	Be prepared to function in a tense, sometimes abrasive atmosphere.<br>
<%=EndAppModParaFont%>

<%=AppModParaFont%>
<%=AppModTitleFont%>
To work better with a High I Leader…
<%=EndAppModTitleFont%>
<%=EndAppModParaFont%>

<%=AppModParaFont%>
&#149;	Be more warm, friendly, and gregarious than you usually are.<br>
&#149;	Be open, but resist the urge to provide all the facts and details.<br>
&#149;	Be tolerant of digressions and interruptions.<br>
&#149;	Engage in give and take, but avoid dominating the conversation.<br>
&#149;	Participate proactively in the decision process, and be decisive.<br>
&#149;	In advancing your ideas, don't rely solely on logic; appeal to feelings and 
emotions.<br>
&#149;	Focus on priorities. Decide what's important and stick with it.<br>
&#149;	Avoid the temptation to be judgmental.<br>
&#149;	Set deadlines and meet them.<br>
<%=EndAppModParaFont%>

