<%=AppModTitleFont%>
To work better with a High S Leader…
<%=EndAppModTitleFont%>
<%=EndAppModParaFont%>

<%=AppModParaFont%>
&#149;	Take an interest in the High S, both as a leader and as a person.<br>
&#149;	Be less introverted and more gregarious than you usually are. Lighten up a little.<br>
&#149;	Be warm, friendly, and sincere. Talk about family and friends.<br>
&#149;	Give plenty of warning when you want to make a change.<br>
&#149;	Concentrate on priorities and on meeting deadlines. Force the pace a little.<br>
&#149;	Don't over-analyze or over-plan.<br>
&#149;	Be prepared to work cooperatively and in a group to achieve common goals.<br>
&#149;	Participate proactively in the decision-making process. Be decisive.<br>
&#149;	Continue to provide logic, facts, and detail, but not too much.<br>
<%=EndAppModParaFont%>

<%=AppModParaFont%>
<%=AppModTitleFont%>
To work better with another High C Leader…
<%=EndAppModTitleFont%>
<%=EndAppModParaFont%>

<%=AppModParaFont%>
&#149;	Be friendly, but don't overdo it.<br>
&#149;	Provide support and backup in difficult situations.<br>
&#149;	Force the pace more than you are used to doing.<br>
&#149;	Deflect pressure whenever possible.<br>
&#149;	Be more upbeat and enthusiastic than you usually are.<br>
&#149;	Prioritize, and help your High C leader focus on what's really  important. Be 
decisive.<br>
&#149;	Don't over-plan, over-organize, or over-analyze. Doing so just fuels the fire.<br>
&#149;	Provide written documentation, but be more brief than you are accustomed to.<br>
&#149;	Provide solutions, not just more data for your High C leader to pore over.<br>
<%=EndAppModParaFont%>
